    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1974-01-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1974-01-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="288"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d288">
                <head>288. Draft Message From the President’s Assistant for National Security
                    Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="from">Kissinger</persName>) to Royal
                    Adviser <persName corresp="#p_AK1" type="to">Adham</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_SBFBAAP1">Prince Saud ibn Faisal</persName> of Saudi Arabia<note
                        n="1" type="source" xml:id="d288fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                            >Kissinger</persName> Office Files, Box 139, Country Files, Middle East,
                        Saudi Arabia, Dec 73–Feb 74. No classification marking. This draft bears
                        markings indicating it was sent to Jidda.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1974-01-22">January 22, 1974</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to oil.]</p>
                <p>“The United States cannot accept a formula for <gloss target="#t_Lifting1"
                        >lifting</gloss> the oil boycott for a fixed period of 90 days only. The
                        <gloss target="#t_Lifting1">lifting</gloss> of the boycott must be on the
                    basis of that proposed by President <persName corresp="#p_SA1">Sadat</persName>;
                    that is, on a ‘most favored nation’ or equivalent basis and without time
                    limit.</p>
                <p>“The United States would be appreciative if, as indicated by <persName
                        corresp="#p_AK1">Shaykh Adham</persName> and Prince <persName
                        corresp="#p_FIAAA2">Faysal</persName>, action to lift the oil boycott could
                    be taken in time for the President to announce the end of the embargo to the
                    Congress in his State of the Union address on January 30.”</p>
            </div>
